                              <td valign="top" style="font-family:Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; color:#333333; font-size:12px; text-align:justify;">It has been about 2-3 years now since the sudden surge in new apartment prices across Mumbai and its peripheral areas. What makes this surge in prices unique is that unlike the previous years (2003-08) the rise in property prices has not been accompanied by a rise in GDP and income growth. In this article, I point-out several indicators that make a strong case for a sharp correction in residential realty prices in Mumbai any time over the next 6-18 months.<br />
  <br />
                                The disconnect between apartment prices and income levels could well be at an all-time high in Mumbai at present. A comparison of apartment prices and income levels in Mumbai and New York, both economic power-houses of their respective countries, provides some food for thought. The house to income ratio in Mumbai is an astounding 54X compared to New York&rsquo;s 26X. And this is after assuming a nearly 100% increase over and above the official per capita income estimate released by the state economic survey, which is 125,000 per annum as of 2010-11.<br />
  <br />
